Yes, it is possible to achieve this by using the `visibility` property in CSS. You can set the visibility of the text to `hidden` by default, and then change it to `visible` on hover using the `:hover` pseudo-class. Here is an example of how you can do this:

```css
p {
  visibility: hidden;
}

p:hover {
  visibility: visible;
}
```

With this CSS code, the text inside the `<p>` element will be hidden by default and will only be visible when the user hovers over it with their mouse.

If you have text stored in an array and you want to display it inside a `<p>` element on hover, you can achieve this using JavaScript. You can create a function that sets the text content of the `<p>` element to the text from the array when the user hovers over it.

Here is an example code snippet that demonstrates how you can achieve this:

HTML:
```html
<p id="hoverText">Hover over me to display the text</p>
```

JavaScript:
```javascript
const textArray = [
    '<img src="https://cdn.glitch.global/f4cb3da3-e38f-4c57-8538-cd16160b85b3/539561ldsdl.jpg?v=1710171387673" class="center" alt="The Admiral House, Simon’s Town, Cape of Good Hope" width="400"> The Admiral House, Simon’s Town, Cape of Good Hope (1844) by Lt. Humphrey John Julian <br><br> From the <a href=\'https://collections.britishart.yale.edu/catalog/tms:10760\'>Yale Center for British Art</a>.</p>',
    'This text is in <p></p> but it will not display on hover'
];

const hoverText = document.getElementById('hoverText');

hoverText.addEventListener('mouseover', function() {
    hoverText.innerHTML = textArray[0];
});

hoverText.addEventListener('mouseout', function() {
    hoverText.innerHTML = 'Hover over me to display the text';
});
```

In this example, we have an array `textArray` containing two text elements. When the user hovers over the `<p>` element with the id `hoverText`, it will display the first element of the array. When the user moves the mouse away, the text will revert back to the default message. 

Feel free to customize the text content and styling as needed for your specific use case.

